{{Infobox prepared food | name = Maltese Ftira | image = Malta_ftira.JPG | image_size = 250px | caption = Ftira | alternate_name = | country = [[Malta]] | region = | creator = | course = | type = [[Bread]] | served = | main_ingredient = | variations = Gozitan open ftira | calories = | other = }}
'''Ftira''' is a ring-shaped, [[leavened]], [[Malta|Maltese]] bread with loaf, usually eaten with fillings such as [[sardines]], [[tuna]], [[potato]], fresh [[tomato]], [[onion]], capers and olives.<ref>{{cite news|title=A true taste of Malta|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/why-choose-malta/where-and-what-to-eat-in-malta/|work=The Telegraph|date=10 March 2017}}</ref> Regional variations include [[Gozitan|Gozo]] ftira, which is served more like a pizza than a sandwich. Gozitan ftira is served open with thinly sliced potato over the crust, or folded over like a [[calzone]]. <ref name=repubblica>{{cite book|author=Juliet Rix|title=Malta and Gozo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WmKKCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA68|date=3 December 2015|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-78477-025-9|pages=68}}</ref>
