{{Infobox organization | name = Gibraltar Heritage Trust | bgcolor = <!-- header background color --> | fgcolor = <!-- header text color --> | image = Gibraltar Heritage Trust logo.gif | image_border = | size = <!-- default 200px --> | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = Gibraltar Heritage Trust's logo. | map = | msize = | malt = <!-- map alt text --> | mcaption = | map2 = | abbreviation = | motto = | predecessor = | successor = | formation = {{Start date|1989|05|01|df=y}} | extinction = <!-- date of extinction, optional --> | type = [[Charitable organization]] | status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> | purpose = Heritage conservation | headquarters = The [[Main Guard (Gibraltar)|Main Guard]], 13 [[John Mackintosh Square]] | location = [[Gibraltar]] | coords = {{coord|36.1406|-5.3541|region:GI_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | region_served = Gibraltar | membership = | language = English | general = <!-- Secretary General --> | leader_title = [[Chief executive officer]] | leader_name = Claire Montado | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | leader_title3 = | leader_name3 = | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | key_people = | main_organ = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> | parent_organization = <!-- if one --> | affiliations = <!-- if any --> | budget = | num_staff = | num_volunteers = | website = {{url|www.gibraltarheritagetrust.org.gi}} | remarks = | former name = }} The '''Gibraltar Heritage Trust''' is a [[nonprofit organization|non-profit]] [[Charitable organization|charity]] established by [[Law of Gibraltar|statute]] on 1 May 1989 to preserve and promote the [[cultural heritage|cultural]] [[natural heritage]] of the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]].{{sfn|Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989|p=1}}
==Funding and responsibilities== The Trust collaborates with the [[Government of Gibraltar]] and with private organisations and individuals to preserve and promote Gibraltar's heritage for cultural, educational and tourism purposes.{{sfn|About the Trust}} The Trust is funded through fees from exhibitions, a portion of ticket sales for access to listed properties managed by the [[Gibraltar Tourist Board]] and from donations.{{sfn|Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989|p=7}} Although the [[Gibraltar Museum]] is owned and operated by the government, the Trust has an advisory role and assists in expanding the collection.{{sfn|Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989|p=17}}
==Sites== The Trust maintains a list of historically important buildings and structures, and gives advice on their preservation and restoration. With Gibraltar's long history as a garrison town and [[naval base]], most of the listed structures are military, including [[defensive wall]]s, [[bastion]]s and [[artillery battery|batteries]]. However, the Trust also covers natural attractions and civilian structures such as caves and churches.{{sfn|Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989|p=Schedules 1 and 2}}
Some of the tourist sites for which the Trust coordinates conservation and development lie on the high slopes of The Rock in the [[Upper Rock Nature Reserve]]. These include [[O'Hara's Battery]], the [[RML 17.72 inch gun|100 ton gun]] at [[Napier of Magdala Battery]], the Military Heritage Centre at [[Princess Caroline's Battery]] and the [[Parson's Lodge Battery]].{{sfn|Bennett|Doyle|1998|p=110}} In the late 1990s the trust arranged for the restoration of [[Parson's Lodge Battery]], which in 1884 had three {{convert|10|in}} muzzled loading rifled guns.{{sfn|Ehlen|Harmon|2001|p=104}} The Trust operates the coastal fort, which is open to the public, with examples of artillery from different periods.{{sfn|Finlayson|Fa|2006|p=57}}
==References== '''Citations''' {{reflist|colwidth=30em}} '''Sources''' {{refbegin}} *{{cite web |ref={{harvid|About the Trust}} |url=http://www.gibraltarheritagetrust.org.gi/about.htm |title=About the Trust |publisher=Gibraltar Heritage Trust |accessdate=2012-10-18}} *{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Bennett|first1=Matthew R.|last2=Doyle|first2=Peter|title=Issues in Environmental Geology: A British Perspective |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DoUYEPemXF0C&pg=PA110|accessdate=2012-10-18 |year=1998|publisher=Geological Society|isbn=978-1-86239-014-0|page=110}} *{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Ehlen|first1=Judy|last2=Harmon|first2=Russell S.|title=The Environmental Legacy of Military Operations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kbpS12tpG3AC&pg=PA104|accessdate=2012-10-18 |year=2001|publisher=Geological Society of America|isbn=978-0-8137-4114-7|page=104}} *{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Finlayson|first1=Clive|last2=Fa|first2=Darren|title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&pg=PA57|accessdate=2012-10-18 |date=2006-10-31|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84603-016-1|page=57}} *{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989}} |url=http://www.gibraltarlaws.gov.gi/articles/1989-12o.pdf |title=Gibraltar Heritage Trust Act 1989 |publisher=Government of Gibraltar |accessdate=2012-10-18}} {{refend}}
