[[File:Farmer in Pakistan.jpg|thumb|right|A Pakistani farmer in the village of ''Mahool Baloch'' in the [[Loralai District|Loralai]] district]]
'''Pakistani village life''' is the traditional [[Rural area|rural]] life of the people of [[Pakistan]].
The rural villagers of Pakistan commonly live in houses made of bricks, clay or mud. These typically have two or three rooms which house extended families. In the modern days they are living by making separate home for each family but they don't live way from each other, they are extending their villages by making more homes. In Gongrani, Baluchistan, people live in homes built within cliff-side caves that are connected by walkways.<ref name="Pakistan-ThePeople">{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P8Ee8RaSlUUC&pg=PA18&dq=Village+life%22,+Pakistan:+The+People&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QYSjT9T3A6aMiALA0JHdAw&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Village%20life%22%2C%20Pakistan%3A%20The%20People&f=false|title=Pakistan: The People |author=Black, Carolyn |year=2002 |isbn=9780778793472 |page=18}}</ref> Most of the villagers are farmers but other rural occupations include [[blacksmiths]], hairdressers and tailorers, shepherds.<ref name="Pakistan-ThePeople"/>
The traditional culture of the village is now subject to change due to the effects upon village society from the introduction of modern technology, such as pumps and [[tube well]]s for irrigation.<ref>Knerr, Béatrice (Prof. Dr.). page 104.</ref> Resistance to social and cultural changes exists among Pakistani village inhabitants, and varying methods of managing these changes have been tried.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_village_culture_in_transition.html?id=hduRAAAAIAAJ|title=The village culture in transition. A study of East Pakistan rural society. |author=S.M.H. Zaidi |year=1970}}</ref>
[[Socioeconomic status]] among rural Pakistani villagers is often based upon the ownership of [[agricultural land]], which also may provide [[Social status|social prestige]] in village cultures.<ref>Knerr, Béatrice (Prof. Dr.). page 102.</ref> The majority of rural Pakistani inhabitants livelihoods is based upon the rearing of livestock, which also comprises a significant part of Pakistan's gross domestic product.<ref>Knerr, Béatrice (Prof. Dr.). page 105.</ref> Some [[Livestock in Pakistan|livestock raised by rural Pakistanis]] include cattle and goats.<ref>Knerr, Béatrice (Prof. Dr.). page 106.</ref>
